<!-- 01 INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">Commercial steamer service</p>
    <h2>LA hard water descaling specialists. Pressureless plus pressure plus boilerless coverage.</h2>

    <p>Commercial steamers cook vegetables, seafood, eggs, and delicate proteins at temperatures (212°F atmospheric, 230 to 250°F pressure) that preserve nutrients, color, and moisture better than boiling or sautéing. LA hospital cafeterias, university dining, hotel banquet kitchens, and health-focused restaurants depend on commercial steamers for batch-cooking volume vegetables, seafood preparation, and institutional meal service.</p>

    <p>We service both commercial steamer types across LA County, Orange County, Ventura, San Bernardino, and Riverside.</p>

    <p><strong>Pressureless (Convection) Steamers</strong>: atmospheric pressure operation, fan circulates steam, faster cooking, easier cleaning. <strong>Cleveland Steam Master</strong> (dominant US market, Welbilt parent). <strong>Vulcan VS Series</strong> (VS-3, VS-6, VS-10, the most common LA mid-range). <strong>Groen HyPlus</strong> and <strong>HyTherm</strong> (Welbilt sister brand to Cleveland). <strong>AccuTemp Steam'N'Hold</strong> (premium boilerless design that eliminates traditional boiler maintenance burden).</p>

    <p><strong>Pressure Steamers</strong>: sealed chamber 5 to 15 PSI, faster batch cooking, larger capacity. <strong>Market Forge</strong> (traditional pressure steamers). <strong>Crown Steam</strong>. <strong>Cleveland pressure</strong> models. Hospital cafeterias and large institutional applications most common.</p>

    <p>LA hard water creates a significant maintenance burden for commercial steamers. Boilers, steam generators, and steam injection systems all accumulate scale. <strong>Annual descaling is critical</strong> (similar to combi ovens). About 75% of our LA steamer service calls relate to hard water mineral buildup, not component failure. Diagnosing root cause vs symptom is the practitioner difference, and it saves operators thousands per year in unnecessary parts replacement that scheduled descaling would have prevented entirely. Most LA institutional kitchens we service didn't know annual descaling was a thing until their second deferred-maintenance emergency repair.</p>

    <p>$120 commercial diagnostic, waived with repair. BHGS #A49573 license. EPA 608 Universal #1346255700410. CSLB C-20 HVAC scope. BBB A+. Phones answered 24/7.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02 FAILURE TREE -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container">
    <p class="section-number">Failure tree</p>
    <h2>Typical commercial steamer failures.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Eight failure modes cover roughly 95% of LA commercial steamer service calls. The first item is the dominant cause: scale buildup. Diagnosing scale issues correctly first saves operators thousands in unnecessary parts replacements.</p>

    <ol class="num-list">
      <li><strong>Boiler scale buildup (LA hard water, primary failure mode).</strong> Annual descaling required. Service runs $400 to $700 (descaling chemicals plus labor). About 75% of LA steamer calls trace back to scale.</li>
      <li><strong>Boiler heating element burnout (year 5 to 8).</strong> Scale buildup accelerates element degradation by trapping heat against the element surface. Replacement $480 to $820. Scale-damaged elements often fail at year 5 to 6 instead of normal year 8 to 10.</li>
      <li><strong>Water inlet valve diaphragm wear.</strong> Restricts water flow to the boiler, year 4 to 7. $260 to $420.</li>
      <li><strong>Steam generator pressure relief valve (pressure steamers, safety critical).</strong> Annual testing required. Replacement $290 to $540 when calibration cannot be verified.</li>
      <li><strong>Door gasket compression.</strong> Steam pressure requires tight seal. Year 5 to 8 typical. $290 to $540 replacement.</li>
      <li><strong>Steam trap failure.</strong> Drain blockage means water cannot exit cooking chamber. $290 to $540 service.</li>
      <li><strong>Convection fan motor (pressureless steamers).</strong> Year 7 to 10 typical bearing wear. $480 to $720.</li>
      <li><strong>Control panel and temperature probe failure.</strong> Modern AccuTemp Steam'N'Hold electronic controls plus newer Cleveland and Vulcan electronic interfaces. Year 6 to 10. $480 to $820.</li>
    </ol>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 CONFIGURATIONS -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">Configurations</p>
    <h2>Three steamer architectures, three service profiles.</h2>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Pressureless Convection Steamers (Most Common in LA)</h3>
    <p>Cleveland Steam Master (model 24CGM200 and similar), Vulcan VS-3, VS-6, VS-10, Groen HyPlus, AccuTemp Steam'N'Hold. Single, two, or three-compartment configurations. Each compartment holds 5 to 10 hotel pans. 30 to 60 minute cooking cycles. Atmospheric pressure operation, which means lower mechanical stress on door gaskets and chamber seals than pressure architectures, but the boiler and steam generation systems still need annual descaling.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Pressure Steamers (Larger Volume)</h3>
    <p>Market Forge, Crown Steam, Cleveland pressure models. 5 to 15 PSI sealed pressure chambers. 8 to 12 minute fast cooking cycles. Larger institutional capacity. Hospital cafeteria, university dining, and large hotel banquet kitchens are typical applications. Pressure-vessel safety inspection (pressure relief valve testing) is mandatory annually for compliance and insurance documentation.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Boilerless (AccuTemp Steam'N'Hold)</h3>
    <p>AccuTemp specialty design. Water injected directly onto a heated element instead of generating steam in a traditional boiler tank. Eliminates the boiler scale maintenance burden entirely. Premium pricing $8,000 to $15,000 versus Cleveland Steam Master at $4,000 to $9,000. Year 12 to 15+ service life is realistic because there's no boiler to scale up. Fewer LA shops handle boilerless designs, and the diagnostic differs from traditional steamer service. We have the experience.</p>

    <h3 class="series-h3">Combi Ovens (Different Equipment, Separate Page)</h3>
    <p>Combi ovens combine steam plus convection. Different equipment category with its own service tree. See our <a href="/commercial/oven-repair/combi-oven-repair/">combi oven repair page</a> for Rational, Alto-Shaam, Convotherm, and other combi service.</p>
  </div>
</section>

